  "text": "A question of major interest is how Nrp1 captures LAP. Our previous binding studies suggest that there is more than one site of interaction [CITATION_1] . We identified the arginine-rich C-terminal segment of LAP as a probably binding site to Nrp1 [CITATION_2] . Indeed, a soluble Cterminal LAP peptide (QSSRHRR) inhibited the binding of either free LAP or LAP-TGF-b1 to Nrp1. Furthermore, we found that a short peptide derived from the sequence of the b2 domain of Nrp1 (RKFK) could activate LAP-TGF-b1, suggesting that this is a second site of interaction. It should also be noted that mature TGF-b1 binds directly to Nrp1 [CITATION_3] , but the binding site is unknown. Further studies are required to completely elucidate the interactions between Nrp and TGF-b components.",
